<DocsLayout title="Task Management — Band Docs">
  <h1>Task Management</h1>
  <p>
    A "task" in Band is a single message sent to a coding agent in a chat pane. Each
    workspace can have multiple chat panes; each pane can run its own agent and queue
    messages independently. Band handles the full lifecycle: submission, real-time
    output streaming, abort, and history.
  </p>

  <h2>Submitting a Task</h2>
  <p>
    To submit a task, focus a chat pane in the dashboard (or run
    <code>band chats send --message "…"</code> from inside a workspace) and provide your
    prompt. The prompt is sent to the chat pane's configured coding agent, which begins
    working immediately. Only one task can run per chat pane at a time — if you submit
    another prompt while a task is running, it is appended to the chat pane's persisted
    message queue and starts automatically when the current task completes. Multiple
    chat panes inside the same workspace can run concurrently.
  </p>

  <h3>File Attachments</h3>
  <p>
    You can attach files to your task prompt from the dashboard. Attached files are
    stored in Band's uploads directory (<code>~/.band/uploads</code>) and made available
    to the coding agent as an additional directory. The agent can read these directly —
    useful for screenshots, design mockups, data files, or any reference material the
    agent needs.
  </p>

  <h2>Chat / Task Status</h2>
  <p>Every chat pane reports its current status:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>waiting</strong> — Idle. The chat exists but no task is running.</li>
    <li><strong>running</strong> — The agent is actively processing the prompt. You can see real-time output in the dashboard.</li>
    <li><strong>completed</strong> — The agent finished successfully. The session result includes duration, number of turns, and cost (when supported by the agent).</li>
    <li><strong>failed</strong> — The agent encountered an error, was aborted, or the session ended unexpectedly.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Chat records are persisted in Band's database (workspace ID, chat pane ID, agent
    type, status, session ID, and timestamps), so chat history survives server restarts.
  </p>

  <h2>Real-Time Output Streaming</h2>
  <p>
    While a task is running, Band streams the agent's output to connected dashboard
    clients over Server-Sent Events
    (<code>/api/tasks/&lt;chatId&gt;/stream</code>). The CLI exposes the same NDJSON
    feed via <code>band chats watch</code>. Both surface:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Text deltas</strong> — The agent's reasoning and explanations, streamed in chunks.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool calls</strong> — Each tool invocation (Read, Write, Bash, Edit, Glob, Grep) with its input.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool results</strong> — The output of each tool call (truncated to ~10,000 characters when very long).</li>
    <li><strong>Images</strong> — Screenshots or other images produced during tool execution.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors</strong> — Any errors the agent reports during execution.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you reconnect to the dashboard while a task is running, Band replays the
    in-memory event buffer for the chat so you see the events leading up to the live
    cursor.
  </p>

  <h2>Cancelling a Task</h2>
  <p>
    Click the abort button in the dashboard, or run <code>band chats stop</code> from
    inside the workspace. Band sends an abort signal to the coding agent, which
    terminates the current session. The task is marked as <em>failed</em> with the
    message "Task aborted by user". Cancellation is immediate — the agent's process or
    stream is forcefully closed.
  </p>

  <h2>Queued Messages</h2>
  <p>
    Each chat pane has a persisted message queue. While a task is running you can queue
    additional prompts; when the current task completes, Band shifts the next message
    off the queue and starts it as a new task using the same session ID, so the agent
    keeps its conversation context.
  </p>

  <h2>Chat History</h2>
  <p>
    All chats are stored in the SQLite database (<code>~/.band/band.db</code>). You can
    list chats per workspace and filter by status:
  </p>
  <pre><code>band chats list --output json | \
  jq '.chats[] | select(.status == "running")'</code></pre>
  <p>
    Chat records include the agent type, model, mode, session ID, and timestamps. For
    agents that support session listing (Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode), Band can drill
    into the full session message history through <code>getSessionMessages</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Tips for Writing Good Prompts</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Be specific.</strong> Instead of "fix the bug", say "fix the null pointer exception in the UserService.getProfile method when the user has no email address".</li>
    <li><strong>Provide context.</strong> Mention relevant file paths, function names, or error messages. The agent works faster when it doesn't need to search for context.</li>
    <li><strong>Define success criteria.</strong> Say what the result should look like: "the test suite should pass", "the API should return a 200 status", "the component should render without errors".</li>
    <li><strong>Use project conventions.</strong> If your project has a CLAUDE.md or similar instructions file, the agent will follow those conventions automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Break large tasks into steps.</strong> Instead of one massive prompt, submit focused tasks and use the message queue to chain them together.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
